====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
# {{lb|en|Internet}} A type of [[dance]] with flailing arm motions, popularized by [[social media]] [[website]] [[w:Vine (service)|Vine]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=April 8, 2014| work=Cambio |title=The 7 Different Ways You Can #Yeet|volume= |number= |author=|passage='''Yeet''' is the new twerk and while it may look like nothing more than a full-body flail, there are some very important techniques you need to know before you embark on your own '''yeet''' adventure. Here are seven different ways you can yeet.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=June 1, 2015| work=Noisey |title=Interview: Youtube Star SheLovesMeechie Dances from the Garage to the Stage|volume= |number= |author=David Turner|passage=Meechie's videos reach hundreds of thousands, sometimes even eclipsing the views of the artists' official visuals, but lately his biggest successes are instead dedicated to specific dances like the whip, '''yeet''', and even the still-regional “Hit Dem Folks” dance, which mimics a basketball player dunking.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date= September 22, 2015| work=Grantland |title=A Note on 'Jumpman' by Metro Boomin ft. Drake and Future|volume= |number= |author=Rembert Browne|passage=The '''yeet''' began, culturally, with a Vine of a kid affectionately nicknamed Lil Meatball doing the dance on his school's track.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=October 27, 2016| work=New York Magazine |title=The Death of Vine Makes the Internet a Worse Place|volume= |number= |author=|passage=Especially black teens, who created a disproportionate number of popular Vines and used the social network to demonstrate wit, intelligence, creativity, and comic timing that was rarely given a spotlight elsewhere. That included dance trends like the '''yeet'''.}}
